\begin_layout Itemize
connection with MLE/EM 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L(\rho)=\KL(\mu,\rho K)+\int\rho\label{eq:em}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to this problem is not unique and we propose to regularize
 the problem using an entropic penalty; i.e.
 for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 we propose to minimize w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E(\rho)=\KL(\mu,\rho K)-\alpha\ent(\rho)\label{eq:minimisation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\KL(\mu,\rho K)$
\end_inset

 is the Kullback-Leibler divergence between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ent(\rho)=-\int\rho\log\rho$
\end_inset

 is the entropy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 This requires the solution of a minimization problem in the space of probabilit
y measures.
 We are going to follow a Wasserstein gradient flow approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Wasserstein Gradient Flows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gradient flows are...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{\prime}(t)=-\nabla F(x(t))\label{eq:gf_real}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wasserstein gradient flows are the 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us denote the set of probability measures with finite second moment
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\real^{d}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{P}_{2}(\real^{d})=\left\lbrace \mu\in\mathcal{P}(\real^{d}):\int\norm{x}{2}^{2}\ d\mu(x)<\infty\right\rbrace 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 and we define the 2-Wasserstein distance on this set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
W_{2}(\mu,\nu):=\left(\inf_{\pi\in\Pi(\mu,\nu)}\int\norm{x-y}{2}^{2}\ d\pi(x,y)\right)^{1/2}\label{eq:w2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi(\mu,\nu)$
\end_inset

 is the set of all possible couplings between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 A minimiser of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:w2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 always exists but might not be unique, each minimiser is called an optimal
 transport plan 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Theorem 6.2.4"
key "ambrosio2008gradient"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})\subset\mathcal{P}_{2}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

 the subset of these measures which is absolutely continuous w.r.t.
 the appropriate Lebesgue measure.
 For every pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\nu\in\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

 there is a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 attaining the minimimum of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:w2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=(Id,t_{\mu}^{\nu})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\mu}^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 denotes the unique transport map between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (see, for example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "page 150"
key "ambrosio2008gradient"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 It is easy to check that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\in\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\ent(\nu)<+\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To define gradient flows on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d}),W_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 we also need a notion of curve, among the several definitions proposed
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Chapter 9"
key "ambrosio2008gradient"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 we consider constant speed geodesics: for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\nu\in\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

, the constant speed geodesic originating from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and with endpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{s}:s\in[0,1]\mapsto((1-s)Id+st_{\mu}^{\nu})_{\#}\mu\label{eq:geodesic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\mu}^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the unique transport map between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\#}\mu$
\end_inset

 denotes the push-forward measure 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\#}\mu(A)=\mu(T^{-1}(A))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then consider functionals 
\begin_inset Formula $F:\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})\rightarrow\real$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d}),W_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 and build a gradient flow solving the minimisation problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{\rho\in\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})}F(\rho).\label{eq:gf_min}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The construction of a gradient flow equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 allows us to transform the minimisation problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:gf_min"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into a PDE whose solution is a density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:gf_min"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We will restrict our attention to functionals which are proper (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\rho)<+\infty$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\in\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

), continuous w.r.t.
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}$
\end_inset

 metric (which metrizes weak convergence, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Theorem 4.4"
key "santambrogio2017euclidean"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and coercive.
 Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Definition 2.1b"
key "ambrosio2008gradient"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, a functional 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d}),W_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is coercive if there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\in\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\inf_{\rho\in\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})}\frac{1}{2\tau}W_{2}^{2}(\nu,\rho)+F(\rho)>-\infty.
\]

\end_inset


