\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we are dealing with an optimization problem, it is natural to assume
 that the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is convex in an appropriate sense; in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

 the standard notion of convexity in 
\begin_inset Formula $\real^{d}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to convexity along geodesics: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu,\mu\in\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

 take a geodesic connecting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:geodesic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, then the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

-geodesically convex if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(((1-s)Id+st_{\mu}^{\nu})_{\#}\mu\right)\leq(1-s)F(\mu)+sF(\nu)-\frac{\lambda}{2}s(1-s)W_{2}^{2}(\nu,\mu).
\]

\end_inset

It is easy to see that when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 the above corresponds to the standard notion of convexity, in this case
 the functional is called displacement convex, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

 the above is stronger than convexity, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<0$
\end_inset

 is weaker 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "page 202"
key "ambrosio2008gradient"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last ingredient in the definition of a gradient flow for functional
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d}),W_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a notion of gradient for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 As standard definitions of derivatives do not apply outside vector spaces,
 it is standard practice to replace the gradient in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:gf_real"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

with the sub-gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial F(\mu)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 For any proper, lower semicontinuous, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

-geodesically convex functional 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 belongs to the sub-differential 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial F(\mu)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F(\nu)-F(\mu)\geq\int\langle\xi(x),t_{\mu}^{\nu}(x)-x\rangle d\mu(x)+\frac{\lambda}{2}W_{2}^{2}(\nu,\mu)\label{eq:subdifferential}
\end{align}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\in\mathcal{P}_{2}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "page 231"
key "ambrosio2008gradient"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Equipped with this notion of gradient, we can now define the gradient flow
 equation for a functional 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d}),W_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a solution of the gradient flow equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{t}\rho_{t}=-\nabla\cdot\left(\rho_{t}v_{t}\right)\label{eq:gf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}\in-\partial F(\rho_{t})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Section 11.1.2"
key "ambrosio2008gradient"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Existence of solutions of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:gf"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 given an initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}\in\mathcal{P}_{2}^{ac}(\real^{d})$
\end_inset

 is ensured for all functionals 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 which are proper, continuous and coercive if the sub-differential 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:subdifferential"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is single-valued 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Theorem 11.1.6 and Corollary 11.1.8"
key "ambrosio2008gradient"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The solution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:gf"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}$
\end_inset

 is unique for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda-$
\end_inset

convex functionals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Theorem 11.1.4"
key "ambrosio2008gradient"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In particular we have the estimate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{2}(\rho_{t}^{1},\rho_{t}^{2})\leq e^{-\lambda t}W_{2}(\rho_{0}^{1},\rho_{0}^{2})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t>0,$
\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

 solution of the gradient flow equation with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}^{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

, which shows that the gradient flow is contractive w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

 and non-expansive when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

